    scripture: "Continue in prayer, and watch in the same with thanksgiving.",
    walk: `As your thirty days draw near their close, friend, Paul gives you a word for the rest of your life: *Continue in prayer.* Not "pray for thirty days and then you're done." Not "pray until you've mastered it and can move on." *Continue.* Keep going. Make prayer not a season you pass through but a lifelong practice you never lay down. This is the goal of everything we've walked through — not a completed assignment, but a continued relationship.

That word *continue* means to persevere, to remain steadfast, to keep at it faithfully over the long haul. And honestly, this is where many of us struggle. We can start strong. We can pray fervently for a while. But continuing — staying faithful in prayer through the months and years, through the dry seasons and the busy ones, when the feelings fade and life crowds in — that's the real test. Paul knows it, and so he urges us: *continue.* Don't quit. Keep the relationship going for a lifetime.

Notice Paul adds, *and watch in the same.* To watch means to stay alert, attentive, awake in your praying — not drifting into a sleepy, going-through-the-motions routine, but staying spiritually awake, expectant, paying attention to how God is moving and what He's saying. A continuing prayer life isn't a dull habit; it's a living, alert watchfulness for God at work.

And once again, thanksgiving appears: *with thanksgiving.* A continuing prayer life stays grateful. Gratitude is what keeps prayer from becoming a grim duty over the years. When you continue in prayer *with thanksgiving,* you keep remembering God's goodness, and that keeps the relationship warm and alive across a lifetime.

So as this journey nears its end, friend, hear this charge: *continue.* These thirty days were never meant to be the whole thing — they were meant to start something that lasts the rest of your life. Keep praying. Stay watchful and grateful. Don't let this be a season you finish, but a relationship you continue, all your days.`,
